{% comment %}
  gazelle-layout — THE single source of truth for global page width.
  Added 14 July 2026.

  Why: Horizon's page_width theme setting is "narrow", which the theme resolves to
  --narrow-page-width: 90rem (~1400px). Every June mockup and every gazelle- custom
  section is built to 1200px. Rather than a per-page hack (this replaces the local
  --page-width override that used to live in gazelle-cover-styles.liquid), we set the
  global page width here, once.

  How: --page-width is declared on <body> via the .page-width-narrow class (assets/base.css),
  NOT on :root — so a :root override would be shadowed by the body's own declaration. We
  therefore override on the body element itself. Selector is body.page-width-narrow ONLY,
  deliberately: it is scoped to the current "narrow" setting so the theme-editor page-width
  control stays a live escape hatch — switch the setting to any other preset and this
  override stops applying, restoring native behaviour.

  We mirror the old local hack's formula exactly — calc(1200px + var(--page-margin) * 2),
  i.e. 1200px of content plus the preset's own --page-margin gap (native preset math). We
  override --page-width ONLY. --page-content-width is deliberately left at the preset value
  (90rem); it feeds --util-page-margin-offset (carousel / edge-offset elements), so it is the
  first suspect if any edge-aligned element misaligns after this change.

  Emits a {% style %} block only — no markup. Rendered from layout/theme.liquid, adjacent to
  the gazelle-fonts hook (last in <head>, so it wins equal-specificity ties).
{% endcomment %}

{% style %}
  body.page-width-narrow {
    --page-width: calc(1200px + var(--page-margin) * 2);
  }
{% endstyle %}
